						<div class="content-canvas__inner u-typo">
							<p>From the beginning of the 1840s, thanks to the written accounts of Ludwik Michał Pac, General Chrzanowski, along with several officers who were members of the former Army Corps prepared a <em>Map of Former Poland, with surrounding areas of neighboring countries, according to updated materials</em>, containing 48 leaves. This is how, in 1859, “the only topographical map of Poland and its historical borders, created and published during the Partitions by Poles with Polish cooperation” comes to be (Piotr Grabowski). Indeed, one could say that this map, depicting the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth of 1772 (as conceived alike by emigrants, conspirators, and national activists), was created so as to be used during the next national uprising. “Unfortunately, it did not serve its purpose, because only a few copies made it to the country, and what is more, it unfortunately did not indicate where the forests were” (Jan Wendt). This flaw can be clearly seen on the sheet depicting the Radom area.</p>
