							<p>The fragments shown here come from a sectional map (scale 1:2500). Lindley’s drawing is seen as “the peak of Warsaw cartography, an artistic drawing with a precision that had no equals in Warsaw cartography” (Weszpiński). Aside from including settlements, differentiated as made of wood or stone, and indicating different modes of use, one notices the green, both of entire terrains, including parks and cemeteries, as well as individual trees. In 1897, the suburbs are green, as are most of the courtyards, awaiting the next wave of economic development. The handwritten version of the map was used later; newly constructed developments and buildings in the suburbs were sketched in.</p>
